<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; WORKER BURNED IN EXPLOSION RELEASED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MACK REED 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Rocketdyne employee was released Tuesday from the Sherman Oaks Burn Center, 
after treatment for burns he suffered in a July 26 explosion that killed two of 
his co-workers at the aerospace contractor's plant near Simi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 "I feel in pretty good shape, for the shape I'm in," said Lee Wells, 62, of 
Newbury Park. 
</P>
<P>
 Wells said doctors grafted skin from his thighs onto his arms and an ear that 
were badly burned when 10 pounds of rocket propellant ingredients exploded on a 
test stand at Rocketdyne's Santa Susana Field Laboratory two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
 The blast killed Larry A. Pugh, 51, a Thousand Oaks engineer, and Otto K. 
Heiney, a Canoga Park engineer who had been standing closer to chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
 Wells said Tuesday his memories of the explosion are "pretty doggone foggy. 
All I could remember was I was over at the sidelines and then I felt the impact 
and I was on the ground." 
</P>
<P>
 Wells said he still suffers a little pain on his thighs, from which healthy 
skin was taken to replace the burned skin on his arms. 
</P>
<P>
 Rocketdyne officials are investigating the explosion and said they expect to 
announce findings next week. MACK REED 
</P>
</TEXT>
