<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANOTHER HAZARD ON LINKS; INSECTS: GOLFERS AT GRIFFITH PARK ARE DONNING MOSQUITO 
NETTING TO KEEP PESKY GNATS OUT OF THEIR FACES. THE BUGS' APPEARANCE IS 
ATTRIBUTED TO A CLEANER LOS ANGELES RIVER. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERIC SLATER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Few golfers have pushed the fashion envelope beyond plaid pants. Until now. 
</P>
<P>
 At the two Griffith Park golf courses, jungle wear has become de rigeur , with 
many morning duffers donning mosquito-net hoods before teeing off. The latest 
accessory has little to do with looks and everything to do with golf. And 
gnats. Which don't seem to mix. 
</P>
<P>
 "Could you imagine trying to make a nice shot with 20 flies going up your 
nose?" asked Kevin Regan, pest-control adviser for the city Recreation and 
Parks Department. 
</P>
<P>
 To deal with the infestation of so-called buffalo gnats in Los Angeles -- 
believed caused, ironically, by a cleaner Los Angeles River -- serious golfers 
have come up with the novel remedy. And at $3.99 apiece, the Griffith Park Golf 
Shop has done decent business, moving 500 of the white headdresses in three 
months. 
</P>
<P>
 Golf course supervisors know of only one other way to combat the buzzing black 
clouds. "Smoking a cigar," said Ralph Hyde, a course supervisor. "Cigarettes 
don't work." 
</P>
<P>
 The tiny insects, also known as black flies, are rising out of a 20-mile 
stretch of the Los Angeles River, from about Studio City to Elysian Park, in 
numbers never before seen -- or swatted or swallowed. 
</P>
<P>
 Just about anyone within a mile or so of the river who has cause to leave the 
house in the morning or evening is suffering -- even Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
 An enterprising baseball fan and cosmetics saleswoman turned a few miserable 
Dodger players on to a skin conditioner known as an exceptional insect 
repellent with a lovely scent. 
</P>
<P>
 Several joggers and cyclists circling Griffith Park one recent evening 
employed the swatting-and-spitting method. Others strapped on surgical masks to 
avoid an unintentional after-dinner snack. 
</P>
<P>
 And as though a mouthful of insects weren't bad enough, the insects bite back. 
</P>
<P>
 Male flies spend their two or three days of life harmlessly, if obnoxiously, 
hunting for and eating pollen, according to Regan, but the females prefer 
blood. 
</P>
<P>
 "The females have to feed on blood before they can return to the river and 
deposit their eggs," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Known to scientists as Simuliidae simulius, the insects appear to be hatching 
in the greatest numbers along a stretch of the river that has a natural rock 
bottom, rather than concrete. 
</P>
<P>
 The larvae attach themselves to river rocks before floating to the surface via 
air bubbles, drying themselves off and venturing off in search of food. 
</P>
<P>
 The theory scientists are working with to explain the extreme outbreak is an 
ironic one: More than a decade spent cleaning up reclaimed water from treatment 
plants may be aiding the hatch. The insects thrive in well-aerated, clean and 
fast-moving water. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are making a black fly habitat," said Mike Mullin, a water biologist for 
the city.  
</P>
<P>
 The insects love it. 
</P>
<P>
 Prompted in part by irate golfers demanding their greens fees back, officials 
are formulating a battle plan. 
</P>
<P>
 The Southeast Mosquito Abatement District is planning a program where a 
naturally occurring bacteria that kills the insects in the larval stage would 
be injected into the stream. The district is working with the mayor's office to 
secure about $50,000 for the program. 
</P>
<P>
 The bacteria could be introduced as soon as Friday, according to abatement 
district spokeswoman LuAnn Munns, but it would probably be two weeks or so 
before the air begins to clear. 
</P>
<P>
 In the meantime, those living, working or playing near the river will have to 
rely on personal ingenuity to repel the pests. 
</P>
<P>
 Golfer John Michael -- not the jungle-net type -- took to pulling his black 
T-shirt over his face and making semi-blind chip shots at a Griffith Park 
course. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA081094-0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 068529 </DOCID>
