<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: COMPTON; COUNTY OFFERS 
COMMUNITY MEDIATOR TO CALM TENSION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Seeking to calm reaction to the videotaped beating in Compton of a 17-year-old 
Latino youth by a black policeman, Los Angeles County officials are offering 
the assistance of the county ombudsman and Human Relations Commission to serve 
as "nonpartisan" mediators. 
</P>
<P>
 The Board of Supervisors voted unanimously Tuesday to offer the services for 
90 days, to promote "community dialogue and understanding, neighborhood peace 
and racial harmony." 
</P>
<P>
 "The level of emotion being experienced in Compton and the questions being 
raised about the long-term impact of this incident should be addressed in a 
sensitive and forthright manner," said Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke, who, 
with Supervisor Gloria Molina, sponsored the motion. "We do not need more 
divisiveness and ethnic tensions in L.A. County." 
</P>
<P>
 The July 29 incident focused attention on festering racial tensions in a city 
that is largely governed by black officials but whose population is 
increasingly Latino. 
</P>
<P>
 Latino leaders have compared the incident to the videotaped beating of black 
motorist Rodney G. King by white police officers. Protesters have gathered 
outside Compton City Hall, demanding apologies from the mayor and the 
resignation of the police chief. 
</P>
<P>
 No Compton officials could be reached to comment on the county's offer. LOS 
ANGELES COUN 
</P>
</TEXT>
